story:
There are currently 2.5 million people living with cancer in the UK, and this is set to grow to almost 4 million by 2030.

Over the next three years, were aiming to raise £500,000. This amount could fund 25,000 hours of care from health professionals, supporting over 1,500 people affected by cancer. Already Warner Leisure Hotels are on the way to achieving this total, raising over £100,000 during the first five months of the partnership.

Team members have launched themselves into fundraising by trekking mountains, running marathons, cycling and even climbing over Londons iconic O2 Arena.

In addition to team members taking part in brilliant activities, Warner have been engaging their guests with our messaging and exciting fundraising events. They have a full and exciting calendar of fundraising activity planned, including a 'Go Mad Go Green' event, charity walks, entertainment evenings, and coffee mornings.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
On the 21st of February 2021, Laura got her Angel wings. On the same day, we all  lost a beautiful wife, a loving mother, a devoted daughter, a caring sister and dear friend.  

Those that knew Laura will remember how touched she was when; just before she started her cancer treatment journey; she donated her beautiful hair and her loved ones helped her to raise money for charity when she set up a just giving page.  So, because Laura has blessed us all with a legacy of memories, her family thought that instead of sending flowers for her funeral, she might like those who loved her to help her give others some memories to cherish with their loved ones. 

Laura’s family are organising some beautiful flowers for her funeral and would kindly ask that instead of sending more that you use that money to support a charity that was very dear to Laura’s heart.  Laura appreciated the support that she got from Macmillan. Her family and friends also valued Macmillan as a source of sound reliable knowledge that they had gained from the years of research that they had carried out.  

Those who knew Laura, would know that she had such a kind heart and loved to help others. She would be so pleased that another cancer patient and their family could have access to the same support that she and her family did during her cancer journey and she would be touched if she could be a part of giving that to them.  That’s why her family have picked Macmillan.

story:
Thanks for supporting our fundraising. We are the Macmillan Benefits Team based at Citizens Advice Bassetlaw. We offer benefits advice to anyone affected by cancer in the Bassetlaw area. Outside of work we enjoy raising money for Macmillan as well. Last year our fundraising efforts had to move to a virtual setting which gave us the opportunity to create fun Facebook videos to help raise money online. 

We see first hand the impact cancer has on peoples lives on a daily basis and we want to do everything we can to help people at that difficult time in their lives. 

At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
Spring is the season of new beginnings for all. It is slowly getting warmer; the grass is getting greener and the air feels a bit fresher. It is the perfect time of year to make plans,  so this Spring why not Spring into Action for St John Ambulance  Sedgley and Upper  Gornal Unit and support our volunteers as they continue to raise funds and  step forward to give vital support to those in need across the country.  Since the beginning of the COVID-19 outbreak our volunteers in St John have given an incredible number of hours of support to patients in hospitals across the country, and we are not stopping. Throughout the year St John  are continuing to mobilise thousands of volunteers to support the rollout of the COVID-19 vaccination. We will need funds to maintain our activities supporting the NHS in our COVID-19 response. The emergency is on-going, and our volunteers will continue to step forward to give vital support. 

So please help us in Sedgley and Upper Gornal Unit  in our 2021 fundraising challenge to help our charity. 

Thank you!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: 100km in April for British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story: We are a team of over 50s riding in memory of our dear friend Tony Bradbury. Our aim is to cycle from Ibstock to Whitby some 180 miles on June 24th/25th. We are not setting a target as anything we can raise between us will be greatly appreciated in these difficult times for life saving charities. Many thanks for your support from all of the silly buggers taking part in this challenge.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Kier Group has selected the British Heart Foundation, the biggest independent funder of cardiovascular research in the UK, as its new corporate charity partner. The two-year partnership will help in the charitys aim of increasing awareness of cardiovascular disease, raise £250,000 for vital research in to heart and circulatory conditions as well as train 1,500 Kier colleagues in the lifesaving first aid, CPR.

The British Heart Foundation is funding life saving research to help end heartbreak for the seven million people in the UK living with cardiovascular disease. For over 50 years it has pioneered research that has transformed the lives of people living with heart and circulatory conditions and has been pivotal to offering vital treatments that are changing the fight against heart disease.
title: Kier Group and the British Heart Foundation partnership

story:
Thanks for visiting our page. We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation and we would be so grateful for your support. 

As you might be aware one of the British Heart Foundations main arms of research is into Strokes. Very sadly Dave Evans suffered a life altering and devastating Stoke last summer. Many of you will also be aware that Grandma Byrom volunteered for many years at a BHF shop. It therefore seemed like the perfect charity to jointly support and take part in a  challenge to raise money for. Whilst getting out for the lock-down allowed walks and trying to work on recovery and strengthening Rebecca's ankle we have hit max 10km a week (40km a month) on average.... so this challenge is asking us to double this! A small 2.67KM a day! Wish us luck. 

Every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks, Gareth and Rebecca

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
In memory of John Starkey we are raising money for British Heart Foundation. 

Dad sadly passed away on 16th February 2021. Our Dad was one of the very best, Everyone who knew him, loved him. Over his 61 years Dad had made lots of friends who he shared lots of memories with him. From when he was a little boy in Birmingham to the great man he was today. Dad loved his life, married to Janet with three children Sarah (me) Rachel & Chris. He loved his grandchildren dearly Harry, Sophia, Jay & Millicent, Even though he didn't get to meet Millicent he would've loved her as much as his other Grandchildren. 

Dad had may struggles in his life after his accident at work which over the years put him into a wheelchair after many operations. Even with him being in so much pain and suffering he always put his family and friends first. 

We are heartbroken that he's gone but with your support we can raise money for this charity which was so close to my Dads heart and now ours.

Thank you for your donation x

His Heartbroken family Janet, Sarah, Rachel, Christopher & Family x

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. 

In 2019, we lost my dad Tom and my partner Simon's dad Ken to heart disease. Both had undiagnosed heart problems and we lost them too soon. 

As I've just turned 40, I'd like to do something positive in their memory, so will be running a total of 40 miles over 40 days. Although I exercise regularly, I'm not a regular runner, so wish me luck!

Thanks for your support,

Sally

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Go on knock our socks off!

story:
I’m raising money for a charity that means a lot to me after being inspired by 11-year-old Max Woosey, who is camping in a tent in his garden for a whole year!

I’ll be joining ‘Max’s Big Camp Out on Saturday 27th March and I’d be so grateful for any donations.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails.

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
The sponsored walk thats good for the sole.

Your small steps will help Guide Dogs make giant leaps. Just one week of stepping can make a difference to the life of children and adults living with sight loss. Raise over £50 (£25 for children) and well replace those worn out socks with a brand-new Guide Dogs pair designed by an international fashion icon!

How your funds will change lives...

-	£50 could pay for fun, tactile activities to help children co-ordinate their muscles and movements.

-	£96 could pay for an eye test each for two guide dogs in training

-	£116 could buy a Training School Kit for one of our guide dog trainers who will teach pups the specialist skills they need as fully qualified guide dogs.

-	£710 could buy a Birthing Kit containing all the essential equipment for a guide dog mum to safely deliver her puppies.

Its thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!

story:

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Vimyonk & Mother0fChickens present to you- The Easter Keg Hunt Tournament

(delayed one week due to conflicting dates with Boomer Games)

This event will go on over two days, 10/04/21 - 11/04/21.

Contestants will have an allotted amount of time to gather as many kegs/gunpowder barrels anywhere around the map and each keg is worth a certain amount of points, the team with the most points wins the round. There will be four rounds that will last one hour each. There will be five sloops each round with one galleon for hosts (Vimyonk, Mother0fChickens, plus two more). The winners of each round will go on to the final which will be held on 11/04/21- Rules for the final are to be announced!

We have chosen to support GOSH because of the great response from the Sea of Thieves community to the Sails of Hope, and one of our own community members spent a long period of time in the care of GOSH.

Thank you to everyone involved, contestants, donators and viewers, you're all heroes!

story: The Great North Run is the biggest half marathon in the world. Run from city to coast as the Red Arrows roar overhead. Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children starts here.

story:
We are celebrating the life of Tom Chandler who died peacefully at home in the early hours of 24 March 2021 after a short illness, aged 93. He was married to Lily Louise Chandler for nearly 72 years and had three children, eleven grandchildren and five great-grandchildren. He will be missed by us all. 

In his final weeks he received compassionate care from the Marie Curie nursing team as well as the Christchurch Palliative Care team. We would like to thank them all for their support.

Instead of flowers for the funeral we would welcome donations to Marie Curie in thanks for their help and to allow them to help others in the same way.

Please feel free to leave messages and memories of Tom.

story:
Through the various lockdowns in 2020, Looe Community Players has been busy rehearsing our play readings weekly and in entertaining our supporters through Zoom performances. For our next performance 'Play-by-Play7' on June 24th 2021 we are pleased to nominate the following local cause to benefit from our thespian talents:

In 2010 the D-Class Inshore Lifeboat Ollie Naismith was officially named and went on service at Looe. The lifeboat was named after a popular local teenager Ollie Naismith who sadly died in a tragic road traffic accident in 2009. Ollies parents, Maxine and John Naismith spearheaded a fundraising campaign to raise the funds for the lifeboat which has gone on to save many lives in and around Looe including the life of Louis Webber, a young local lad who was of a similar age to Ollie. The lifeboat is now coming to the end of its operational life so the team at Looe Lifeboat station are teaming up with the Naismiths and Webber family to launch the Looe Lifeboat Appeal to raise the £78,000 required to provide a replacement lifeboat which will be named the Ollie Naismith II. Your donation to this community appeal will help to fund this lifeboat which will continue the selfless work of our volunteer lifeboat crew in Looe.
title: Looe Community Players - 'Play-by-Play7'

story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
This page has been created in loving memory of Trevor Skinner, who sadly passed away on the 22nd March 2021.

Over the last 13 years, Trevor dedicated most of his time to working with Oxfam. Through his dedication and commitment he continually raised funds to help those in poverty to build better lives. 

In honour of Trevor's memory, he had requested that in lieu of flowers,  memorial donations are made to Oxfam to continue supporting this charity, which was so very close to his heart.

Thank you, for your generosity and kindness.

Richard, Kathryn and Sheila

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Pete always had love & compassion to give. Those of you who knew him will have experienced this. What you may not have known was that he was very passionate about supporting the charity Wateraid.

When a community gets clean water for the first time, it’s the start of something truly life-changing. 

Right now, some of the worlds poorest and most marginalised people don't have clean water to drink. Without access to water, overcoming poverty is just a dream. By donating to help us dig a well you're changing the lives of children for the better. They can dream again. 

In memory of Pete, if you would like to do something, we're asking for donations to sink a Semi-Deep Well. This offers a medium- long term solution for areas where water is harder to find and deeper digging is necessary for clean water. They are mostly dug in remote areas where access to cheap water is a luxury. 

Your donation will change people's lives and carry on making a dream of Pete's a reality. 

With love from  Anne, Emma & Thom and Andy& Emma X
